# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# combined — __neg__, __pos__, __abs__ across all 10 asyncio subjects
#
# Covers the full matrix: 10 classes x 3 methods = 30 rows.
# __neg__: false for all 10 — unary negation is not defined for any type.
# __pos__: false for all 10 — unary plus is not defined for any type.
# __abs__: false for all 10 — abs() is not defined for any type.
# All 30 values are false.
# asyncio types are designed for coroutine-based concurrency — their entire
#   API surface is expressed through await, async with, async for, and
#   explicit method calls. No numeric data model protocol is implemented:
#   waves 658–669 established that all arithmetic (__add__/__sub__/__mul__),
#   division (__truediv__/__floordiv__/__mod__), power/shift, bitwise logical,
#   reflected arithmetic, reflected bitwise, and in-place augmented assignment
#   operators are absent from all 10 asyncio types. The unary numeric operators
#   __neg__, __pos__, and __abs__ follow the same pattern.
# asyncio.Event note: Event manages a simple boolean flag (set/clear/wait);
#   numeric magnitude has no meaning for a two-state boolean guard.
# asyncio.Lock/Condition note: mutual-exclusion synchronization objects;
#   there is no numeric state to negate, preserve, or take the absolute value of.
# asyncio.Semaphore/BoundedSemaphore note: the permit counter is encapsulated
#   and not exposed through any numeric data model method, including unary ones.
# asyncio.Queue note: Queue is an ordered item store; items are managed
#   through put()/get() coroutine calls; abs(queue) and -queue are not defined.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

